WEBVTT

00:00.866 --> 00:08.397
Father in Heaven, would you take these few moments and help us to pursue our joy in Jesus?

00:08.517 --> 00:14.066
In gathering here, we are coming with at least a small expression of desire.

00:14.206 --> 00:25.042
To be at the conference, to be in the session, we want to enjoy Jesus Christ in the habits of our lives and in particular, the means of your grace.

00:25.223 --> 00:27.506
And so would you provide clarity here for us?

00:27.810 --> 00:31.053
Would you not leave our hearts unmoved and unstirred?

00:31.594 --> 00:36.739
Would you provide opportunities and our minds and imaginations for steps forward?

00:37.700 --> 00:39.862
And would it all be to the greater enjoyment of your son?

00:39.922 --> 00:41.604
In Jesus' name we pray.

00:42.845 --> 00:43.145
Amen.

00:44.667 --> 00:54.056
A few years ago, I was picking up some college students and posed the question to myself, what is the most important truth I learned in college?

00:54.977 --> 00:56.178
All right, my brain.

00:56.706 --> 01:17.009
trying to think all the different details, all the different facts, liberating discoveries I made, not just in political science, which was my major in college, not just in doing pre-dental, I thought it was gonna be a dentist, but mainly in what I was learning about Jesus and about the Christian faith and about how God impacted my life.

01:17.450 --> 01:20.433
Rodney talked about the book, Desiring God, that was true for me too.

01:20.994 --> 01:24.498
The end of my freshman year in college, my world was turned around

01:25.154 --> 01:28.539
through reading with friends, the book Desiring God.

01:28.599 --> 01:34.887
And so here's how I put that answer to the question a few years ago to these college students.

01:35.788 --> 01:54.674
I said, for me, the single most important breakthrough in all my college learning was finding that God is not just the appropriate focus of the verbs believe, trust, fear, obey, worship.

01:56.162 --> 02:03.690
but also he is the most fitting and most satisfying, most worthy focus of the verb.

02:05.653 --> 02:06.193
Enjoy.

02:08.476 --> 02:24.914
As far as I can tell, the single most important thing God did in those trajectory shaping formative years of college, yes, believe God, trust in him, fear him with holy fear, obey him, worship him,

02:26.786 --> 02:28.308
Do you enjoy Him?

02:30.050 --> 02:39.163
And I love that this weekend isn't only about that, and the session isn't only about that, but this church is about that, and that's a beautiful thing.

02:40.244 --> 02:56.466
And when we say enjoy, mark this, you can use enjoy in really small ways that seem insignificant, and you can use enjoy in big ways that have tremendous life-changing significance.

02:57.218 --> 03:03.606
So when we're talking enjoy, we're not talking about the small enjoyment of chuckling at a clever commercial.

03:04.667 --> 03:12.537
We're talking about the large enjoyment of basking before an ocean or a mountain or the Grand Canyon.

03:14.019 --> 03:26.674
We're not talking about the thin enjoyment of humming along with a pop song, but the thick enjoyment of coming to the long anticipated symphonic climax

03:27.426 --> 03:30.931
or of a great novel, the apex.

03:31.993 --> 03:42.590
We're not talking about the shallow enjoyment of acquiring some new gadget, but the deep enjoyment of reconnecting and catching up with some old friend.

03:44.993 --> 03:55.730
Not only does God invite us and command us to believe him, trust him, fear him, obey him, worship him, but to enjoy him.

03:57.698 --> 04:03.103
We've already quoted in this conference Psalm 34, 8, oh, taste and see that the Lord is good.

04:04.444 --> 04:04.985
Enjoy Him.

04:06.446 --> 04:10.951
And after John's session last night, I couldn't help but think of Isaiah 55.

04:11.171 --> 04:12.933
I don't know if anybody else thought Isaiah 55.

04:12.953 --> 04:26.866
The Apostle John and the prophet Isaiah have some glorious similarities, including the fact that they love talking about drink and hunger.

04:28.002 --> 04:31.586
about thirst and about having bread and rich fare.

04:33.048 --> 04:56.914
So my mind went here last night as John talked about thirst and hunger from John's gospel to Isaiah chapter 55, which really relates to what we're after here this afternoon, where God Himself through Isaiah is like a street vendor, like somebody walking up and down the aisles of AT&T Stadium

04:58.530 --> 05:01.154
offering up their peanuts or whatever.

05:01.634 --> 05:21.101
It's a very humbling thing that God Himself would posture Himself like a street vendor and He would say to us, He would say, come, everyone who thirsts, come to the waters and you who have no money, come buy and eat, come by wine and milk without money and without price.

05:21.722 --> 05:27.410
Why do you spend your money for that which is bread and your labor for that which does not satisfy?

05:28.450 --> 05:35.920
Listen diligently and come to me," he says, and delight yourselves in rich food.

05:38.162 --> 05:45.312
And so we might say, with the help of the Holy Spirit, yes, I want to eat like that spiritually.

05:46.173 --> 05:53.122
I want to drink like that spiritually, but how do I eat Jesus?

05:55.424 --> 05:56.626
How do I drink?

05:57.634 --> 06:02.661
Jesus, how do I enjoy Jesus?

06:05.164 --> 06:10.451
And so we as Christians sometimes talk about the spiritual disciplines.

06:11.793 --> 06:12.734
It's not my favorite term.

06:14.977 --> 06:22.748
I would rather have the S, B capital, Holy Spirit, spiritual, and sometimes disciplines.

06:23.269 --> 06:27.314
And I feel like the language falls on me first and foremost.

06:27.394 --> 06:28.515
What am I gonna do?

06:28.536 --> 06:33.322
Rather, I like talking about habits of grace.

06:34.904 --> 06:36.807
The grace comes first.

06:37.167 --> 06:38.128
God's given His grace.

06:38.649 --> 06:39.891
He's offering His food.

06:41.373 --> 06:51.446
And He's inviting us to posture our lives, to have rhythms of life, to have habits in our lives that would help us to have the posture of receiving His grace.

06:52.227 --> 06:53.529
This is not, hey, you do it.

06:53.909 --> 06:54.951
You do something spiritual.

06:55.131 --> 06:57.394
This is the God of all grace.

06:57.762 --> 07:01.947
is streaming his grace in his appointed channels.

07:02.308 --> 07:06.053
Will you align aspects of your life with his ongoing grace?

07:06.894 --> 07:08.376
That's what we're talking about in this session.

07:09.197 --> 07:14.824
I remember as a college student reading spiritual disciplines books, and we do this on the college campus.

07:14.844 --> 07:15.865
Hopefully you do this in the church.

07:15.905 --> 07:23.655
You talk about reading the Bible and meditating on scripture and memorizing scripture and sharing your faith and praying alone, praying with others.

07:23.716 --> 07:25.618
We can talk about these disciplines, fasting.

07:26.370 --> 07:28.672
After a while, I was like, man, that's a long list.

07:30.254 --> 07:38.162
I see why people became monks because if I was to do everything in that list, I could not be a student anymore.

07:38.182 --> 07:39.924
I wouldn't have a job someday.

07:39.944 --> 07:42.026
It may not be a very good father or friend.

07:44.449 --> 07:46.451
So the long list can be intimidating.

07:47.672 --> 07:53.298
And what I found helpful a few years ago in trying to teach these disciplines to college students is to think,

07:53.442 --> 07:54.804
What's really the heart of it?

07:54.824 --> 07:58.330
What's the principle beneath the potential practices?

07:58.791 --> 08:01.075
I don't think you need to be doing all the practices at all the times.

08:01.936 --> 08:04.059
What are the principles beneath the practices?

08:06.283 --> 08:09.729
I'll give you my summary in just a minute of those principles.

08:10.310 --> 08:15.498
But first, let's hear from an old voice on these means of grace.

08:15.518 --> 08:20.306
This is J.C. Ryle, favorite of mine, over 100 years ago.

08:20.962 --> 08:27.990
Talking about these means of grace, this may be my favorite means of grace, quote, outside the Bible.

08:28.670 --> 08:29.211
Here's Ryle.

08:30.112 --> 08:32.775
Help us, J.C. Ryle, with what are the means of grace?

08:32.815 --> 08:42.626
He says, the means of grace are such as Bible reading, private prayer, and regularly worshiping with the church.

08:44.568 --> 08:50.034
Wherein, one hears the word taught and participates in the Lord's Supper.

08:50.946 --> 08:52.007
So we've got three there.

08:52.508 --> 08:53.048
Is that a fourth?

08:53.068 --> 08:54.570
Is that a fifth?

08:54.590 --> 08:56.633
Somewhere three to five, he's mentioning.

08:57.273 --> 08:58.615
And here's what he says about it.

08:59.997 --> 09:15.275
I lay it down as a simple matter of fact that no one who is careless about such things must ever expect to make much progress in sanctification, in holiness, in Christian growth.

09:16.716 --> 09:18.258
I can find no record

09:18.754 --> 09:22.880
of any respectable saint who ever neglected the means of grace.

09:24.482 --> 09:33.195
They are appointed channels through which the Holy Spirit conveys fresh supplies of grace to the soul."

09:35.078 --> 09:35.598
Well, I want that.

09:35.638 --> 09:36.500
Anybody here want that?

09:37.141 --> 09:42.709
Fresh supplies of grace for your soul from the Holy Spirit.

09:43.490 --> 09:46.354
Sign me up.

09:46.658 --> 09:50.584
He strengthens the work he has begun in the inner person.

09:52.046 --> 09:54.931
Our God is a God who works by means.

09:56.173 --> 10:04.205
And he will never bless the soul of that man who pretends to be so high in spiritual that he can get on without God's means.

10:07.550 --> 10:15.122
So in seeking God's ongoing grace in our Christian lives, in seeking ongoing joy in Jesus,

10:16.098 --> 10:19.922
God would not have us just walk around in the wilderness.

10:20.422 --> 10:21.644
I like to get a little grace here.

10:22.565 --> 10:25.528
Could you drop some grace on me while I walk around?

10:26.989 --> 10:29.832
Rather, God tells us where he's going to pour out his grace.

10:30.613 --> 10:43.506
He tells us where his waterfalls are, what are the waterfalls of his grace so that we can align our little lives with his ongoing, ongoing flow of grace.

10:44.418 --> 10:57.436
And even better than having appointed channels and fresh supplies of grace for the soul is that's more personal way we're talking in this conference about enjoying Jesus more deeply.

10:57.456 --> 11:05.286
I'd rather talk about enjoying Jesus more deeply than the more impersonal way of talking about ongoing grace.

11:05.607 --> 11:06.408
That's good, that's true.

11:06.828 --> 11:07.770
It is ongoing grace.

11:09.152 --> 11:13.938
And it's enjoying Jesus or experiencing more of Jesus

11:14.146 --> 11:15.267
That's what we're after.

11:16.349 --> 11:17.290
There's a means.

11:18.392 --> 11:20.394
There is an end to the means.

11:21.736 --> 11:25.341
When we talk about means, means means there's an end.

11:25.361 --> 11:27.344
There's a goal in mind.

11:27.704 --> 11:28.185
What is that?

11:30.007 --> 11:31.990
I'll give you three texts I like to go to.

11:32.410 --> 11:35.094
One of them is new as of this last week.

11:36.896 --> 11:38.258
1 John 17, 3.

11:38.914 --> 11:40.716
This is eternal life, Jesus says.

11:40.836 --> 11:41.938
This is the night before he dies.

11:42.398 --> 11:45.322
He's praying out loud that his disciples can hear him.

11:45.342 --> 11:57.217
And he says, this is eternal life, that they, my disciples, would know you, Father, the only true God, and Jesus Christ whom you have sent.

11:58.879 --> 11:59.499
Oh, this is amazing.

12:00.721 --> 12:01.622
This is eternal life.

12:02.924 --> 12:08.050
Not just the ability to keep living and do what you want, earthly ways,

12:08.642 --> 12:09.583
This is the heart.

12:09.663 --> 12:16.272
This is the essence of the life he offers, knowing, personally knowing, communing with his father.

12:16.292 --> 12:20.578
And he's so bold as to say, and Jesus Christ.

12:21.799 --> 12:22.820
And me, he says.

12:22.860 --> 12:24.563
Here it is, right at the heart.

12:25.083 --> 12:29.910
Knowing Jesus is the heart of what Jesus is offering, his disciples.

12:30.310 --> 12:32.313
Or Philippians 3.8, I hope you know it and love it.

12:33.454 --> 12:36.338
Paul says, I count everything is lost.

12:36.546 --> 12:42.736
because of the surpassing worth of knowing Christ Jesus, my Lord.

12:44.258 --> 12:45.820
One of my favorite texts of all time.

12:46.221 --> 12:46.922
Here's my new one.

12:47.804 --> 12:53.252
I was assigned to preach John 10 at our church this past Sunday on The Good Shepherd.

12:54.414 --> 12:59.602
And verses 14 and 15 of John 10, just walloped me.

12:59.778 --> 13:02.041
I can't believe this is here.

13:02.401 --> 13:05.505
How have I not lingered over this and appreciated this more?

13:05.525 --> 13:10.292
How has this not been one of my end of the means text for years talking to my habits of grace?

13:10.392 --> 13:12.214
So here it is, John 10, 14 to 15.

13:12.795 --> 13:14.437
Jesus says, I'm the good shepherd.

13:15.999 --> 13:17.441
I know my own.

13:19.223 --> 13:20.164
Not just know who they are.

13:20.465 --> 13:21.005
I know them.

13:21.166 --> 13:25.491
I know my own, he says, and my own know me.

13:25.551 --> 13:27.634
That is spectacular.

13:28.130 --> 13:28.891
I know them.

13:28.931 --> 13:32.495
They know me, but he's not done.

13:32.535 --> 13:40.545
Then he says, just as the father knows me and I know the father.

13:44.310 --> 13:48.255
So Jesus compares, he puts together, he doesn't say, it's not a contrast.

13:48.555 --> 13:50.017
He doesn't say they're different.

13:50.958 --> 13:53.141
He says, they're alike.

13:53.161 --> 13:54.002
They're similar.

13:54.498 --> 13:57.821
Just as Jesus knows his father and the father knows the son.

13:57.881 --> 14:06.770
So just as he says, I know my sheep, I know my own and my own, know me.

14:09.072 --> 14:10.253
And what's that knowledge like?

14:10.293 --> 14:18.621
That eternal life of knowing Jesus, the surpassing worth Paul calls it of knowing Jesus, knowing the shepherd.

14:20.022 --> 14:20.643
What's that like?

14:22.024 --> 14:23.826
It's not boring.

14:26.114 --> 14:30.078
It's not blah or meh, vanilla.

14:31.299 --> 14:37.545
It's not something to be indifferent about or apathetic about, but the emphasis of this weekend.

14:38.486 --> 14:46.333
It is something to profoundly enjoy the surpassing value of knowing Christ Jesus, my Lord.

14:46.353 --> 14:48.715
So here's how I'd say the end of the means.

14:48.835 --> 14:51.138
I'm gonna talk about spiritual disciplines, I promise.

14:52.359 --> 14:54.180
But I wanna talk about where it's going.

14:54.220 --> 14:55.922
What's the end of the means?

14:56.290 --> 15:01.295
The end of the means, the goal is knowing and enjoying Jesus.

15:02.996 --> 15:05.839
So I love the focus that enjoy brings.

15:06.500 --> 15:10.043
Here's my three part summary then of the habits of grace.

15:10.063 --> 15:21.574
If you take our list of 12 or 15 or 20 or 25 potentially helpful spiritual practices, here's my summary of the three main principles at work in them.

15:23.396 --> 15:25.938
Number one, hear his voice.

15:26.786 --> 15:29.209
Number two, have his ear.

15:29.249 --> 15:34.975
Number three, belong to his body.

15:34.995 --> 15:38.359
I think that way of slicing the pie covers the whole field.

15:38.379 --> 15:39.119
You get this pie.

15:39.920 --> 15:41.322
The means of grace pie.

15:42.023 --> 15:47.128
What can we do to be ongoing recipients of God's grace that we might know and enjoy Jesus?

15:48.049 --> 15:50.592
I think you could cut that pie in 12 pieces if you really wanted.

15:50.792 --> 15:51.953
That's too confusing for me.

15:53.535 --> 15:56.178
I'm really helped to cut this thing in three pieces.

15:57.250 --> 16:02.635
I think Riles kind of, he's kind of doing two clear pieces and he's like, do three, maybe a third or fourth.

16:03.356 --> 16:04.797
Let's just do three clear pieces.

16:05.879 --> 16:11.824
You hear God's voice, we hear God's voice in his word, in scripture.

16:12.625 --> 16:16.769
Not just walking around, voices in your head, the voices in your head are from you.

16:16.809 --> 16:23.616
The voice from the book on the page by the spirit is from God.

16:23.876 --> 16:25.618
You hear his voice in his word.

16:26.562 --> 16:30.328
And second, we have his ear in prayer.

16:31.650 --> 16:32.532
This is amazing.

16:32.772 --> 16:39.422
He doesn't only speak to us, but he pauses and he stoops and he wants to hear back.

16:39.443 --> 16:40.624
It's a relationship.

16:41.526 --> 16:43.369
He wants to hear from us in light of what he said.

16:43.429 --> 16:49.799
And third, we belong to his body in the fellowship of the local church.

16:50.420 --> 16:51.682
He's not just me and Jesus.

16:53.265 --> 16:54.226
He speaks

16:54.882 --> 17:08.663
and he wants me to respond and he gives me fellows, he gives me a community, he gives me people, not just people that float in and out of my life and happen to love Jesus too, but a commitment in a local church.

17:09.404 --> 17:23.346
People saying, I'm gonna be the church to you, you be the church to me, and he has a means of grace for us in the uncomfortable and often wonderful and often uncomfortable lives of the local church.

17:24.066 --> 17:25.228
Now, a quick question here.

17:25.328 --> 17:27.371
You might ask, what about other habits?

17:28.613 --> 17:31.838
What about the habit of getting adequate sleep?

17:33.761 --> 17:50.066
What about the habit of getting normal human movement with my body that my blood flows and gets oxygen to my brain and neurotransmitters to my brain and I can have a more healthy normal human life

17:50.178 --> 17:56.726
because I'm living less sedentary than our vehicles and screens encourage us in the 21st century, exercise.

17:57.406 --> 17:58.888
Or what about food?

18:00.430 --> 18:04.895
We all know you can eat and drink certain things that have effects on the body.

18:06.317 --> 18:10.381
Often we ignore them or don't feel them, but there are particular times where you feel the effect.

18:11.363 --> 18:14.026
What we do in these physical lives affects our souls.

18:14.807 --> 18:17.810
We are a soul body intermingling

18:18.594 --> 18:21.599
And what we do in the one affects the other.

18:21.639 --> 18:22.901
We're whole persons.

18:23.983 --> 18:26.587
And so you're sleep and you're bodily movement.

18:27.028 --> 18:29.071
And what you eat does affect the soul.

18:29.111 --> 18:40.990
I'd put these sleep, exercise, daily bread in the category of assistance to the means of grace.

18:41.711 --> 18:44.656
I would not count them as means of grace on their own.

18:45.116 --> 18:46.098
The Bible doesn't do that.

18:47.202 --> 18:52.149
The Bible has many things to say about these in an important but assistant role.

18:54.432 --> 19:03.104
And the clear teaching of scripture throughout is the preciousness, the importance, the promise of God's word to us.

19:04.787 --> 19:12.818
Our words back to him in prayer and that we don't do this alone, but with others in the community of the Christian life.

19:13.378 --> 19:15.100
So let me take it backwards in this session.

19:15.480 --> 19:19.385
Just about everywhere I go and do this, I always go word, prayer, fellowship.

19:20.606 --> 19:25.412
I thought, what if we change it up for Stone Gate one time?

19:26.253 --> 19:27.114
I'm gonna go backwards.

19:27.434 --> 19:28.295
I've never done this before.

19:28.395 --> 19:31.299
Can you tell me afterwards if this worked or not?

19:31.319 --> 19:32.180
I'm gonna go backwards.

19:32.460 --> 19:34.202
Let's start with fellowship.

19:35.463 --> 19:38.667
Then we'll come to prayer and then we'll finish onward.

19:40.129 --> 19:41.330
I think we can do it that way.

19:41.730 --> 19:44.112
Though there'll be a little trick, a little wrinkle there.

19:44.293 --> 19:46.495
I'll try to mention that to you when we get to it.

19:46.715 --> 19:50.599
So number one, and three main points for you in the session.

19:50.699 --> 19:54.483
Number one, enjoy Jesus in his people.

19:56.746 --> 19:58.828
Belong to his body.

20:00.389 --> 20:07.297
And not just formally belong with your names in the membership roster, but functionally belong.

20:07.317 --> 20:08.658
Rhythms of life.

20:10.434 --> 20:16.664
It's vital in the Christian life to have habitual covenant community.

20:17.766 --> 20:25.559
Christian faith is fed and it thrives and it's healthy in habitual covenant community.

20:26.461 --> 20:30.147
And it's often lacking when we don't have others in our lives.

20:30.628 --> 20:31.629
It can go south quick.

20:32.411 --> 20:36.818
Maybe you remember just a few years ago in the struggles

20:36.994 --> 20:41.581
with a global pandemic and not knowing what the effects were going to be and taking various precautions.

20:41.601 --> 20:43.965
And we should not meet and we should have distances.

20:44.405 --> 20:46.669
That was not good for a lot of people's Christian faith.

20:49.433 --> 20:54.841
We didn't fully appreciate how good it is to have fellows in our lives.

20:55.983 --> 20:59.268
I got twin texts here on fellowship for you.

20:59.288 --> 21:03.154
I think maybe the two most important texts in the New Testament or in the Bible,

21:03.618 --> 21:08.848
on how other people are a means of God's grace in our lives come from the book of Hebrews.

21:10.932 --> 21:11.934
So we've got a Bible with you.

21:12.095 --> 21:13.477
If you want to go to Hebrews with me.

21:15.361 --> 21:17.525
Hebrews chapter three, Hebrews chapter 10.

21:18.006 --> 21:21.473
Since we're doing stuff backwards today, let's go to Hebrews 10 first.

21:23.116 --> 21:26.162
This is Hebrews 10, 24 and 25.

21:32.994 --> 21:47.592
Hebrews 10, 24 and 25 says, let us consider how to stir up one another to love and good works, not neglecting to meet together, as is the habit of some.

21:48.553 --> 21:49.154
There is habit.

21:50.816 --> 21:56.463
That's the only word translated habit in my ESV New Testament.

21:56.723 --> 21:58.806
If you got some other translation, you may have more than one habit.

21:59.767 --> 22:02.450
There's a word in Greek, you could translate habit in other places.

22:02.658 --> 22:06.924
Here's the one habit in the ESV, and it says, here's a habit not to have.

22:09.068 --> 22:19.844
Do not neglect to meet together as some are making a habit, but encouraging one another and all the more as you see the day drawing near.

22:21.406 --> 22:23.069
The observations here on Hebrews 10.

22:23.629 --> 22:32.082
First, the paradigm here is that the many in the church are watching out for the sum.

22:33.282 --> 22:56.178
You've got the healthy many and you've got an eye out for some, some who are weak, some who are struggling, some who are going through some difficulty, some who are running on empty, and apparently Christians are in each other's lives enough to see that and move toward it.

22:56.358 --> 23:01.426
And not just wait for the some who are struggling to bring themselves forward and ask for help.

23:03.394 --> 23:08.161
But to know the sum, know each other enough, see me.

23:08.662 --> 23:11.125
Say, brother, are you doing okay?

23:12.287 --> 23:13.789
Sister, how are you?

23:13.849 --> 23:20.739
And in the original here, there's no word how.

23:20.879 --> 23:23.683
You may have that word how in your translation.

23:23.783 --> 23:26.827
Let us consider how to stir one another up.

23:27.548 --> 23:30.332
So you may think like, oh, let me think of different ways here.

23:30.392 --> 23:31.474
How might I stir up

23:32.258 --> 23:33.019
A fellow human.

23:33.219 --> 23:34.160
Oh, I'll think of my list.

23:34.180 --> 23:37.984
I'll make my practical list of how to stir up the love and good deeds.

23:38.925 --> 23:40.186
There's no how here.

23:40.226 --> 23:41.667
I see whether it isn't a translation.

23:41.727 --> 23:43.389
It's a tough translation, tough word.

23:43.409 --> 23:44.670
It would read really strange.

23:45.291 --> 23:48.714
It would read like, consider one another unto stirring up.

23:49.375 --> 23:51.637
Most people would be like, what does that even mean?

23:51.657 --> 23:52.177
Here's what it means.

23:53.939 --> 24:00.946
It's not that the actions you're going to take is the object of your considering is the other people are.

24:02.050 --> 24:11.519
You know other people well enough to consider them, to not just think, all right, how do you motivate general humanity to love and good deeds?

24:11.579 --> 24:12.420
Now I'll apply that.

24:12.560 --> 24:15.383
Rather, how do I know this person?

24:16.083 --> 24:16.624
I know him.

24:16.704 --> 24:17.405
I know Bob.

24:18.846 --> 24:19.667
I know Cecil.

24:21.208 --> 24:27.754
And so I'm thinking, given my knowledge of him, my relationship with him, how might I provoke him to loving good?

24:30.076 --> 24:31.698
How might I use, here's another observation.

24:31.842 --> 24:37.209
Words, Christian fellowship involves no coercion.

24:38.971 --> 24:47.121
I know this is Texas, but no guns are involved in how we encourage each other to love and good deeds.

24:50.144 --> 24:52.187
Words have this amazing power.

24:53.188 --> 25:01.298
If we thought about it enough, this is like magic that you would have a thought

25:01.794 --> 25:03.977
in your head, somebody else can't see it.

25:05.378 --> 25:10.104
And you would verbalize it with your breath, speak it into the air.

25:10.164 --> 25:11.686
And you can't see it, it's just in the air.

25:13.368 --> 25:20.116
And it could go into this hole in the side of somebody, say, hey, we have holes in the sides of our heads for these words.

25:21.698 --> 25:27.585
And that the word would go through the air into their hole, down into their heart.

25:29.007 --> 25:31.410
And it might feed their faith

25:32.418 --> 25:35.702
It might keep them afloat when they're struggling.

25:35.983 --> 25:41.410
It might be the spiritual food they need and feel too weak to get for themselves.

25:43.413 --> 25:46.277
Because hearing is so easy.

25:47.218 --> 25:52.285
That's why Paul would say faith comes from hearing and hearing from the Word of Christ.

25:53.266 --> 25:54.488
He didn't say faith comes from reading.

25:54.548 --> 25:58.593
Reading takes a little more energy, a little more effort.

25:59.855 --> 26:02.098
Sometimes you got a brother and sister not ready to

26:03.138 --> 26:05.380
I feel like they got it to put in the effort.

26:06.402 --> 26:12.848
And you can put a word in their soul through their ear and feed their faith.

26:14.130 --> 26:17.033
This is how we are means of grace to each other.

26:17.053 --> 26:21.538
And the last one here is, he talks about not neglecting to meet together.

26:22.699 --> 26:26.483
The meeting together of God's people is essential.

26:26.503 --> 26:32.850
This is our single most important habit as a church that we would meet together.

26:33.218 --> 26:41.127
that we would hear God's word together, that we would pray together, worship together, and then before and after, oh, we talk.

26:42.948 --> 26:43.709
And it's so good.

26:43.729 --> 26:44.971
That's not small.

26:45.491 --> 27:02.930
You might call it small talk, but before and after church, it is not small that God's people interact and hopefully find ways to ask spiritual questions and give spiritual encouragement to know each other

27:03.746 --> 27:05.989
You've got to help each other and be God's means of grace.

27:07.211 --> 27:07.692
Other text.

27:08.974 --> 27:09.535
Hebrews 3.

27:12.419 --> 27:14.062
This is Hebrews 3, 12 and 13.

27:14.082 --> 27:23.255
Take care, brothers, lest there be in any of you an evil, unbelieving heart leading you to fall away from the living God.

27:24.617 --> 27:33.010
But exhort one another every day as long as it is called today that none of you may be hardened by the deceitfulness of sin.

27:35.266 --> 27:43.058
All right, so note that language again of any, there's a big group of healthy Christians in the church.

27:43.639 --> 27:54.956
There's some or any or a few that any given season could fall through the cracks, struggling spiritually.

27:55.376 --> 28:01.746
Here an evil, unbelieving heart is in some.

28:02.946 --> 28:05.329
and that leads them to fall away from the living God.

28:05.830 --> 28:07.091
It doesn't happen all in one moment.

28:07.652 --> 28:08.353
It's incremental.

28:08.734 --> 28:15.102
There may be some great fall that happens, but that was, they were incremental.

28:15.142 --> 28:27.358
They were degrees leading up to it day after day of slow hardening that could be interrupted by Christian relationships, by us being a means of grace in each other's lives.

28:27.999 --> 28:30.162
That's why there's this daily focus.

28:31.458 --> 28:33.020
It doesn't have to technically be today.

28:33.040 --> 28:37.826
You don't have to be in a accountability relationship where you necessarily check in every single day.

28:39.628 --> 28:43.453
But the emphasis here is on this regular vigilance.

28:43.473 --> 28:59.794
The hardening of a heart by sin happens in these gradations, these increments day by day so that we would know each other regularly and be a means of grace to each other is critical in intercepting each other from falling away from the living God.

29:01.410 --> 29:04.234
There's an attentiveness in each other's lives.

29:04.254 --> 29:04.875
That's a part of it.

29:05.536 --> 29:07.279
And then here again, there's this power of words.

29:07.319 --> 29:09.782
He says, exhort one another.

29:11.485 --> 29:17.273
It's translated encouraging in Hebrews 10 and exhort here, but it's the same word.

29:18.635 --> 29:24.103
Basically means use helping words, use words that help somebody else.

29:25.225 --> 29:28.530
If they're in danger and they need a word of warning, help them with a warning.

29:29.250 --> 29:35.537
Or if their tank is low and they're in need of strength, encouragement, food, help them that way.

29:35.577 --> 29:40.142
These are helping words in the context of regular relationships.

29:40.162 --> 29:44.666
So we put grace into the ear through the ear hole.

29:46.969 --> 29:55.698
We get a chance in fellowship to be God's voice to our brothers and sisters and for them to be God's voice to us.

29:57.506 --> 30:04.237
be not only his hands and feet, but be his voice as a mutuality in this means of grace.

30:05.138 --> 30:08.964
All right, number two, enjoy Jesus in prayer.

30:11.629 --> 30:13.952
Enjoy the gift of having his ear.

30:17.478 --> 30:20.843
Here's where we got to do a little work because we're doing them out of order, in a sense.

30:24.209 --> 30:25.010
Logically,

30:25.570 --> 30:31.176
Word comes first, or sequentially, God's Word comes first, and then we respond in prayer.

30:31.776 --> 30:32.577
He's the Creator.

30:33.298 --> 30:33.859
We're creatures.

30:35.100 --> 30:35.720
He's Father.

30:36.021 --> 30:36.621
We're children.

30:37.502 --> 30:38.323
He goes first.

30:39.044 --> 30:39.745
He initiates.

30:41.767 --> 30:50.135
People probably don't do this anymore, but I remember being in college 25 years ago, and sometimes we'd gather in a prayer gathering, and we'd say, who wants to dial up?

30:51.877 --> 30:52.818
Who wants to pray first?

30:55.138 --> 30:56.220
That wasn't a great way of doing it.

30:57.081 --> 31:01.207
Because nobody really dials up God in prayer.

31:01.468 --> 31:02.529
He always dials up.

31:03.471 --> 31:04.533
He speaks first.

31:05.314 --> 31:06.636
He made the world first.

31:07.177 --> 31:08.539
He created you first.

31:09.040 --> 31:14.248
Whenever you come and pray to Him, you are praying in view of some conception you have of Him.

31:14.869 --> 31:17.933
Whether it's just pagan or whether it's informed by the Bible.

31:18.594 --> 31:23.602
Prayer is a response to God's revelation of Himself or

31:23.778 --> 31:27.724
at least our sense of who he is and are praying to him.

31:27.925 --> 31:29.167
So prayer is responsive.

31:30.489 --> 31:34.916
And it's part of this relationship where he speaks first and we respond.

31:36.478 --> 31:43.529
So prayer goes well after hearing from God.

31:45.032 --> 31:49.138
And in my devotion times in the morning, I may pray a brief word.

31:49.719 --> 31:51.442
God help me, help me here as I read.

31:52.226 --> 31:53.708
Help me here as I linger in your presence.

31:54.570 --> 31:57.915
But I'm mostly saving my prayer for after I've heard from him.

31:57.955 --> 32:03.603
I want to hear from him and then let his word to me then inform my prayers.

32:03.903 --> 32:09.772
I want to pray in the suite of what he's saying in his word.

32:10.834 --> 32:14.539
I want to hear his word and then go, oh, that was good, whatever, pivot.

32:14.559 --> 32:15.541
Now I'm going to pray my list.

32:15.881 --> 32:17.484
Just totally ignore what you said, God.

32:18.085 --> 32:19.206
I'm just going to pray my list.

32:19.527 --> 32:21.650
Get them on the table, check that box and go.

32:22.210 --> 32:29.077
Rather, prayer is, yes, Father, I hear what you say, and now I want to speak back to you.

32:29.237 --> 32:31.979
I want to respond to you in light of what you are saying.

32:32.360 --> 32:51.218
This morning, in your word, to me, by the power of your spirit, having heard from God, I want to turn His promises, His warnings into prayer for myself, for my wife, my kids, my church, my friends, roommates,

32:51.938 --> 32:56.022
Younger believers, non-believers, coworkers, neighbors, the nations.

33:00.346 --> 33:03.389
The prayer is a relational response to God's voice.

33:05.852 --> 33:08.374
I'm sure many have heard this before, if not everybody.

33:10.856 --> 33:18.644
A way of thinking through the various aspects of prayer is this acronym, Acts, A-C-T-S.

33:19.905 --> 33:20.786
I know it's well known.

33:22.082 --> 33:23.904
I'm not sure how well practiced it is.

33:25.186 --> 33:31.074
Because we have this instinct of prayer is asking, I'm gonna come and I'm gonna ask God.

33:31.094 --> 33:32.616
And he wants to hear from us.

33:32.656 --> 33:33.778
He does want to hear from us.

33:34.559 --> 33:38.083
And it's so important to remember the other dynamics in prayer.

33:38.103 --> 33:39.185
So acts goes like this.

33:39.525 --> 33:41.228
A is adoration.

33:43.190 --> 33:52.082
And especially when we come talking about enjoying God, this is, this should be, this can be, the most enjoyable aspect of prayer to adore him.

33:52.258 --> 33:56.142
to praise Him before rushing to what we want to ask Him for.

33:56.302 --> 33:57.544
Give me this, give me that, give me that.

33:58.205 --> 34:01.728
Before rushing there to say, Father, you are majestic.

34:02.830 --> 34:03.791
You are sovereign.

34:03.971 --> 34:07.515
You're holy to praise Him for what you see in His Word.

34:07.715 --> 34:10.498
You have been gracious to us in Jesus Christ.

34:10.698 --> 34:11.760
You gave your own Son.

34:11.840 --> 34:17.586
You've promised to give us all things in Him to adore Him, to linger in your adoring.

34:18.018 --> 34:19.860
Your soul was made to adore.

34:20.080 --> 34:26.007
There is something deeply satisfying in admiration of the living God.

34:26.568 --> 34:34.858
The rarest of pleasures, admiration, and adoring is a chance to linger in that, enjoy Him in adoring Him.

34:35.659 --> 34:39.203
And then naturally flowing from adoring Him is confession.

34:41.085 --> 34:45.330
Confession of my sin, confession that I don't measure up,

34:46.626 --> 34:56.438
Confessing my need for his help, that loneliness of confession is a fitting counterpart to appreciating and adoring him in his highness.

34:58.220 --> 35:03.426
Then there's Thanksgiving, that's the T. A-C-T, Thanksgiving.

35:04.327 --> 35:08.512
Thank him for his many provisions in our lives.

35:08.532 --> 35:13.618
In the speed of modern life, we pause to be grateful so little

35:14.114 --> 35:18.440
And here in Christian prayer is a chance to practice that over and over.

35:19.080 --> 35:22.425
And some have the practice nowadays of start today with things you're thankful for.

35:23.586 --> 35:26.370
Christians have had that for 2,000 years.

35:26.790 --> 35:27.431
It's called prayer.

35:27.491 --> 35:37.524
It's an aspect of our prayer, rehearsing gratitude, thanking God and not just thinking of things I'm glad I have in my secular mind.

35:37.565 --> 35:41.810
I'm thanking God for them, the one who actually gave them.

35:42.466 --> 35:47.832
And then finally, now supplication, you open the floodgates, it's easy to ask.

35:47.852 --> 35:58.165
We're inclined to ask, ask for myself, for my family, neighbors for work, move out in concentric circles, ACTS.

35:58.765 --> 36:04.512
Let me give you briefly four councils here for pursuing enjoyment in prayer.

36:06.014 --> 36:09.618
One is, come with focus and clarity.

36:12.866 --> 36:16.611
You don't have to earn God's ear with a long prayer.

36:18.113 --> 36:19.936
I got to have a certain amount of time.

36:19.956 --> 36:22.579
I got to put in my time that God will hear me.

36:23.360 --> 36:24.822
That's not how it works with a Father.

36:26.404 --> 36:36.338
Matthew 6, right before He gives us the Lord's Prayer, which is only 50 words, we very rarely hear prayers that short, 50 words.

36:36.834 --> 36:43.583
Right before he says, when you pray, do not heap up empty phrases like the Gentiles do, for they think they'll be heard for their many words.

36:43.823 --> 36:44.985
Don't be like them.

36:46.247 --> 36:49.331
Your father knows what you need before you ask him.

36:51.233 --> 36:52.175
You gotta earn his ear.

36:54.518 --> 36:56.821
Second, seek to pray spiritual prayers.

36:58.283 --> 37:04.912
In our tendencies to ask for the next dollar, the next meal, the next tangible thing, which he wants to hear.

37:05.493 --> 37:06.514
Our tangible needs.

37:07.138 --> 37:09.380
Sometimes we can forget to pray spiritual prayers.

37:10.602 --> 37:31.785
Like the Apostle Paul prays in Ephesians 1, 16 to 19, he prays that the Lord Jesus Christ, the God of our Lord Jesus Christ, the Father of glory, may give you a spirit of wisdom and of revelation in the knowledge of him, having the eyes of your hearts enlightened, that you may know what is the hope to which he's called you.

37:33.688 --> 37:35.890
Prayers like Philippians 1, 9 to 11.

37:36.258 --> 37:43.708
Colossians 1, 9-12, 2 Thessalonians 1, 11, spiritual prayers for spiritual good in our own lives and others.

37:44.009 --> 37:48.315
Third, pray out loud or in writing.

37:50.137 --> 37:53.923
It really helps to form and finish thoughts.

37:54.764 --> 38:03.416
Not just let it be amorphous here in the head, but if somebody else is in the house, you can whisper them on your lips.

38:03.796 --> 38:04.978
You can write them down.

38:06.722 --> 38:08.204
form and finish your prayers.

38:08.304 --> 38:09.866
Finally, pray with others.

38:13.031 --> 38:18.459
And maybe one of my favorite quotes here from Tim Keller's book on prayer has to do with praying with others.

38:18.539 --> 38:28.993
He says, by praying with friends, you will be able to hear and see facets of Jesus that you have not yet perceived.

38:30.295 --> 38:34.281
Praying with others is an amazing way to pursue our enjoyment of Jesus.

38:34.321 --> 38:35.122
To know Him better,

38:36.674 --> 38:39.699
Hear of glories that we haven't been inclined to see.

38:39.719 --> 38:44.486
Hear how they approach him, what they ask of him, a chance to know him.

38:44.506 --> 38:49.173
Now I gotta finish quick with number three.

38:50.395 --> 38:51.937
Enjoy Jesus in his word.

38:54.641 --> 38:56.724
Hear his voice in scripture.

38:57.786 --> 39:00.530
Enjoy Jesus in his word.

39:06.338 --> 39:11.207
I'll give you some quick councils for approaching his word.

39:11.387 --> 39:14.714
Number one, have some modest reading plan.

39:15.515 --> 39:23.510
It is good to have a plan and not just open up to a random place or just reread Titus, reread Philemon again because I got no plan.

39:24.893 --> 39:30.002
You can find so many Bible reading plans online, just Google Bible reading plan.

39:31.330 --> 39:35.676
have some plan so that when you're up early in the morning, you don't have to think through that.

39:35.696 --> 39:36.457
You got a plan.

39:36.477 --> 39:37.558
You got a place you're going to go.

39:37.798 --> 39:43.285
And you take that assignment as this is where the living God means to speak to me this morning.

39:44.467 --> 39:45.268
Here's the assignment.

39:45.949 --> 39:49.433
Here's what he's coming to me with.

39:49.453 --> 39:50.555
Number two, pace.

39:52.598 --> 39:54.800
Find a pace that is worthy of his word.

39:54.820 --> 39:59.186
This may be the most important thing I have to say about personal Bible intake.

40:00.642 --> 40:02.925
Our world is in a hurry.

40:04.367 --> 40:06.931
Screens teach us to read in a hurry.

40:07.231 --> 40:14.121
Our lives are so full of stuff that even when we're not consciously hurrying, we are hurrying down below, subconsciously.

40:14.141 --> 40:28.882
And when you open the Bible and come before God, this is the most important place to not be in a hurry to engage His Word even leisurely.

40:30.114 --> 40:37.826
Slowly, let the word itself dictate the pace at which you should be receiving it and enjoying it.

40:38.727 --> 40:40.910
Now just rushing through to check the box and move on.

40:43.414 --> 40:54.631
And third here, create enough margin to really linger, to check the context, reread, explore related texts, use those cross references down the middle.

40:55.612 --> 40:57.435
The main thing here is to lose track of time.

40:58.356 --> 40:59.538
And I put the phone

40:59.874 --> 41:11.226
Away, I'd try to not sit with a clock in view, but find a way to set yourself up with enough margin to lose track of time.

41:13.088 --> 41:20.015
We don't have the best conversations with spouse, with friends, with anybody when we're watching the clock the whole time.

41:21.216 --> 41:26.802
If you really want to enjoy communion with another person, you need to lose track of time.

41:28.258 --> 41:32.664
which is what we so badly need when we open our Bibles in modern life.

41:32.704 --> 41:39.773
I could say so much here about meditation and some great conversations this weekend with Justin Jackson about meditation.

41:41.375 --> 41:47.723
Rodney talked about, you guys have already mentioned meditation in a sermon series or something he's planning.

41:48.444 --> 41:51.007
There will be more to come from your pastors on meditation.

41:51.588 --> 41:53.911
I'd love to say more, but we need to move on.

41:55.293 --> 41:56.114
Finish up here.

42:00.194 --> 42:02.357
Ooh, I got some Puritan quotes on meditation.

42:02.677 --> 42:03.638
They knew how to meditate.

42:05.080 --> 42:06.342
Some final things here before we're done.

42:06.382 --> 42:08.084
How often?

42:08.505 --> 42:09.846
These are regular questions I get.

42:09.886 --> 42:10.748
How often?

42:12.330 --> 42:17.276
I think God's word rewards daily access.

42:19.299 --> 42:19.559
When?

42:19.599 --> 42:22.322
Ideally first thing in the morning.

42:24.665 --> 42:28.210
Let God's voice be the one that sets the trajectory of your day.

42:28.866 --> 42:36.938
Instead of letting other voices, please don't let the voices of the news and of social media be the first voices you hear in the morning.

42:38.781 --> 42:40.183
Let his voice be first.

42:41.345 --> 42:46.613
You can handle the other voices so much better if you've heard his voice first.

42:48.275 --> 42:48.736
How long?

42:50.358 --> 42:51.881
I don't think there's an easy answer for this.

42:51.901 --> 42:53.022
I'm not going to give you minutes.

42:54.304 --> 42:55.506
I think the main thing is

42:55.682 --> 42:59.006
to find a space where you can lose track of time.

42:59.947 --> 43:01.129
That could happen in 10 minutes.

43:01.730 --> 43:02.871
It could happen in half an hour.

43:03.552 --> 43:04.453
It could happen in longer.

43:05.534 --> 43:12.503
But to set aside enough margin that you can linger unhurried in God's presence through His Word.

43:15.266 --> 43:18.310
So my main charge here has been enjoy Jesus.

43:19.071 --> 43:24.498
That's what we're looking to do in the Word, in prayer, in fellowship, to feast our souls on Him,

43:25.186 --> 43:45.448
come to Him thirsty, wanting to drink from Him, come to Him hungry, wanting to eat, commune with Jesus through feeding on His self-giving word, and then you yourself, giving yourself to Him in return in prayer, and then doing that in the life of the regular life of the local church.

43:47.450 --> 43:50.733
Jesus is supremely enjoyable.

43:52.415 --> 43:55.058
We'll talk more about that this evening.

43:55.362 --> 43:56.464
And tomorrow morning, I'm sure.

43:57.385 --> 44:00.930
And Jesus Himself speaks to us in His Word.

44:01.852 --> 44:05.016
And Jesus wants to hear from us in prayer.

44:05.056 --> 44:15.972
And Christ Himself helps us and gives Himself to us in the covenant life of the local church.

44:17.655 --> 44:18.356
Let me pray together.

44:19.417 --> 44:20.159
It's a Father in Heaven.

44:21.621 --> 44:23.023
We want to be among those.

44:23.243 --> 44:25.266
We want to say from the heart

44:26.498 --> 44:29.841
that we truly know Jesus and enjoy Him.

44:30.702 --> 44:32.584
And we know that knowledge is not perfect.

44:33.765 --> 44:35.908
And we know our enjoyment of Him is not perfect.

44:36.628 --> 44:37.429
It's dynamic.

44:38.470 --> 44:41.653
That vine and branch connection John talked about last time.

44:41.774 --> 44:42.554
It's dynamic.

44:42.574 --> 44:44.356
There are ups and downs in the Christian life.

44:45.637 --> 44:50.082
And yet Father, you have revealed to us the places where your grace is passing.

44:50.382 --> 44:54.066
You have not left it to our guessing or our speculation.

44:54.178 --> 44:57.041
as to how to walk with you and how to know and enjoy Jesus.

44:59.764 --> 45:11.976
And so would you work in us postures of heart and habits of life for enjoying the grace of knowing Jesus in your word and communing with him in prayer.

45:12.216 --> 45:18.642
And that in the context of the mutually up building, mutually encouraging life of the local church.

45:19.944 --> 45:20.865
In Jesus name we pray.

45:22.026 --> 45:22.386
Amen.

